The bug in this Tundra script is that it selects the third row, which has a
an index of 2 because arrays are zero-indexed in most languages (including 
Tundra), rather than one-indexed as common English language might suggest. 
The 'target' value is actually at index 1 in the array.

Correcting this bug would mean changing `rows[2]` to `rows[1]`. Here is the
the corrected program:

```Tundra
val rows = [
  { label: "low", value: 10 },
  { label: "target", value: 20 },
  { label: "high", value: 30 }
];

val selected = rows[1];
print(selected.value);
```
This script now correctly selects the 'target' record from the array and pr
prints its `value`, which should be 20 as expected.
